b'' b'[note, ohio legislation unlike federal legislation, shows the entire' b'law as it would be changed by the legislation. these parts are in' b'all capitals, the rest (i.e., current law is in regular type)].' b'' b'as introduced' b'' b'120th general asembly' b'' b'regular session h. b. no. b'' b'1993-1994' b'' b'represenative beatty' b'' b'a bill' b'' b'to amend sections2923.11, 2923.17,and and' b'to enact section of the revised code' b'to expand the defintion of dangerous ordnance to' b'include military weapons that do not use bolt' b'action, to increase the penalty for a violation' b'of the prohibition against possession of' b'dangerous ordnance, to prohibit any person from' b"acquiring a military weapon on or after the act's" b'effective date, to require the licensure of' b'military weapons acquired for aproper purpose' b"prior to the act's effective dte, to prohibit a" b'person from importing, manufacturing, or selling' b'a military weapon, and to declare an emergency.' b'' b'be it enacted by the general assembly of the state of ohio:' b'' b'section that sections and be' b'' b'amended and section of the revised code be enacted to' b'' b'read as follows:' b'' b'sec. as used in section to of' b'the revised code:' b'(a) "deadly weapon" means any instrument, device, or thing' b'capable of inflicting death, and designed or specially adapted' b'for use as a weapon, or possessed, carried, or used as a weapon.' b'(b)(1) "firearm" means any deadly weapon capable of' b'expelling or propelling one or more projectiles by the action of' b'an explosive or combustible propellant. "firarms" includes an' b'unloaded firearm, and any firearm which is inoperable but which' b'can readily be rendered operable.' b'(2) when determining whether a firearm is capable of' b'expelling or propelling one or more projectiles by the action of' b'an explosive or combustible propellant, the trier of fact may' b'rely upon circumstancial evidence, including, but not limited to,' b'the representations and actions of the individual exercising' b'control over the firearm.' b'(c) "handgun" means any firearm designed to be fired while' b'held in one hand.' b'(d) "semi-automatic firearm" means any firearm designed or' b'specially adapted to fire a single cartridge and automatically' b'chamber a suceeding cartridge ready to fire, with a single' b'function of the trigger.' b'(e) "automatic firearm" means any firearm designed or' b'specially adapted to fire a succession of cartridges with a' b'single function of the trigger. "automatic firearm" also means' b'any semi-automatic firearm designed or specially adapted to fire' b'more than thirty-one cartridges without reloading, other than a' b'firearm chambering only caliber short, long, or long-rifle' b'cartridges.' b'(f) "sawed-off firearm" means a shotgun with a barrel less' b'than eighteen inches long, or a rifle with a barrel less than' b'sixteen inches long, or a shotgun or rifle less than twenty-six' b'inches long overall.' b'(g) "zip-gun" means any of the following:' b'(1) any firearm of crude and extemporized manufacture;' b"(2) any device, including without limitation a starter's" b'pistol, not designed as a firearm, but which is specially adapted' b'for use as a firearm;' b'(3) any industrial tool, signalling device, or safety' b'device, not designed as a firearm, but which as designed is' b'capable of use as such a firearm, when possessed, carried, or' b'used as a firearm.' b'(h) "explosive device" means any device designed or' b'specially adapted to cause physical harm to persons or property' b'by means of an explosion, and consisting of an explosive' b'substance or agency and a means to detonate it. "explosive' b'device" includes without limitation any bomb, any explosive' b'demolition device, any blasting cap or detonator containing an' b'explosive charge, and any pressure vessel which has been' b'knowingly tampered with or arranged so as to explode.' b'(i) "incendiary device" means any firebomb, and any device' b'designed or specially adapted to cause physical harm to persons' b'or property by means of fire, and consisting of an incendiary' b'substance or agency and a means to ignite it.' b'(j) "ballistic knife" means a knife with a detachable' b'blade that is propelled by a spring-operated mechanism.' b'(k) "dangerous ordinance" means any of the following,' b'except as provided in division (l) of this section:' b'(1) any automatic or sawed-off firearms. zip-gun, or' b'ballistic knife;' b'(2) any explosive device or incendiary device;' b'(3) nitroglycerin, nitrocellulose, nitrostarch, petn,' b'cyclonite, tnt, picric acid, and other high explosives; amatol,' b'tritonal, tetrytol, pentolite, pecretol, cyclotol, and other high' b'explosive compositions; plastic explosives; dynamite, blasting' b'gelatin, gelatin dynamite, sensitized ammonium nitrate, liquid-' b'oxygen blasting explosives, blasting powder, and other blasting' b'agents; and any other explosive substance having sufficient' b'brisance or power to be particularly suitable for use as a' b'military explosive, or for use in mining, quarrying, excavating,' b'or demolitions;' b'(4) any firearm, rocket launcher, mortar, artillery piece' b'grenade, mine, bomb, torpedo, or similar weapon, designed and' b'manufactured for military purposes, and the ammunition for that' b'weapon;' b'(5) any firearm muffler or silencer;' b'(6) any military weapon;' b'(7) any detachable magazine, magazine, drum, belt, feed' b'strip, or similar device that has a capacity of, or that readily' b'can be restored or converted to accept, more than fifteen rounds' b'of ammunition;' b'(8) any combination of parts that is intended by the owner' b'for use in converting any firearm or other device into a' b'dangerous ordinance.' b'(l) "dangerous ordnance" does not include any of the' b'following:' b'(1) any firearm, including a military weapon and the' b'ammunition for that weapon, and regardless of its actual' b'age, which employs a percussion cap or other obsolete ignition' b'system or which is designed and safe for use only with black' b'powder, and' b'(2) any pistol, rifle, or shotgun, designed or suitable' b'for sporting purposes, unless the firearm is either of the' b'following;' b'(a) a military weapon as issued or as modified, and the' b'ammunition for that weapon;' b'(b) an automatic or sawed-off firearm.' b'(3) any cannon or other artilery piece which,' b'regardless of its actual age, is of a type in accepted use prior' b'to has no mechanical, hydraulic, pneumatic, or other system' b'for absorbing recoil and returning the tube into battery without' b'displacing the carriage, and is designed and safe for use only' b'with black powder;' b'(4) black powder, priming quills, and percussion caps' b'possessed and lawfully used to fire a cannon of a type defined in' b'division (l) of this section during displays, celebrations,' b'organized matches or shoots, and target practice, and smokeless' b'and black powder, primers, and percussion caps possed and' b'lawfully used as a propellant or ignition device in small-arms or' b'small-arms ammunition;' b'(5) dangerous ordinance which is inoperable or inert and' b'cannot readily be rendered operable or activated, and which is' b'kept as a trophy, souvenir, curio, or museum piece.' b'(6) any device which is expressly excepted from the' b'definition of a destructive device pursuant to the "gun control' b'act of stat. u.s.c. 921(a)(4), as amended, and' b'regulations issued under that act.' b'(m) "military weapon\' means any of the following;' b'(1) any firearm that originally was manufactured for' b'military use, or a copy of any such firearm, if the firearm is' b'not a bolt action firearm;' b'(2) any model of any of the following firearms that is a' b'semi-automatic firearm and is a rifle or any model of any copy of' b'any of the following firearms that is a semi-automatic firearm' b'and is a rifle;' b'(a) armalite ar-180;' b'(b) auto-ordnance thompson models 19