l'" b'(f) holmes mp-83 and mp-22;' b'(g) intratec tec-9 and scorpion b'(h) iver johnson enforcer;' b'(i) ingram mac-10 and mac-11;' b'(j) mitchell arms spectre auto;' b'(k) scarab skorpion;' b'(l) sterling mk-7;' b'(m) uzi pistol;' b'(n) universal enforcer;' b'(o) wilkinson "linda" auto pistol.' b'' b'(4) any model of any of the following firearms that is a' b'semi-automatic firearm and is a shotgun or any model of any copy' b'of any of the following firearms that is a semi-automatic firearm' b'and is a shotgun:' b'' b'(a) franchi spas-12 and law-12;' b'(b) striker and street sweeper;' b'(c) benelli m1 super b'(d) mossberg bullpup;' b'(e) usas-12 auto shotgun.' b'' b'sec. (a)(1) no person shall knowingly acquire,' b'have, or carry any dangerous ordnance.' b'' b'(2) no person shall knowingly use any dangerous ordnance.' b'(b) this section does not apply to any of the following:' b'(1) officers, agents, or employees of this or any other' b'state or the united states, members of the armed forces of the' b'united states or the organized militia of this or any other' b'state, and law enforcement officers, to the extent that any such' b'person is authorized to acquire, have, carry, or use dangerous' b'ordnance and is acting within the scope of his duties;' b'(2) importers, manufacturers, dealers, and users of' b'explosives, having a license or user permit issued and in effect' b'pursuant to the "organized crime control act of stat.' b'952, u.s.c. and any amendments or additions to or' b'reenactments of that act, with respect to explosives and' b'explosive devices lawfully acquired, possessed, carried, or used' b'under the laws of this state and applicable federal law;' b'(3) importers, manufactuers, and dealers having a license' b'to deal in destructive devices or their ammunition, issued and in' b'effect pursuant to the "gun control act of stat. b'18 u.s.c. and any amendments or additions to or' b'reenactments of that act, with respect to dangerous' b'ordnance lawfully acquired, possessed, carried, or used under the' b'laws of this state and applicable federal law;' b'(4) persons to whom surplus ordnance has been sold,' b'loaned, or given by the secretary of the army pursuant to 70a' b'stat. and u.s.c. and any' b'amendments or additions to or reenactments of that act, with' b'respect to dangerous ordnance when lawfully possessed and used' b'for the purpose specified in that section;' b'(5) owners of dangerous ordnance registered in the' b'national firearms registration and transfer record pursuant to' b'the act of october stat.1229, u.s.c. and' b'any amendments or additions to or reenactments of, and' b'regulations issued under the act.' b'(6) carriers, warehousemen, and others engaged in the' b'business of transporting or storing goods for hire, with respect' b'to dangerous ordnance lawfully transported or stored in the usual' b'course of their business and in compliance with the laws of this' b'state and applicable federal law;' b'(7) the holders of a license or temporary permit issued' b'and in effect pursuant to section of the revised code,' b'with respect to dangerous ordnance lawfully acquired, possessed,' b'carried, or used for the purposes and in the manner specified in' b'the license or permit.' b'(c) division (a)(1) of this section does not apply to the' b'acquisition, having, or carrying of dangerous ordnance that is a' b'military weapon if both of the following apply:' b'(1) the person who acquires, has, or carries the dangerous' b'ordnance in question acquired it before the effective date of' b"this amendment as a collector's item or for a legitimate" b'research, scientific, educational, industrial, or other proper' b'purpose;' b'(2) no later than the close of business on the seventh day' b'after the effective date of this amendment, the person who' b'acquired the dangerous ordnance in question in accordance with' b'division (c)(1) of this section submitted an application pursuant' b'to section of the revised code for a license to have and' b'carry it and the application has not been denied or a valid' b'license has been issued to the person.' b'(d) divisions (a)(1) and of this section do not apply' b'to the acquisition, having, carrying, or using of any dangerous' b'ordnance described in division (k)(7) of section of the' b'revised code that was acquired prior to the effective date of' b'this amendment.' b'(e) whoever violates this section is quilty of unlawful' b'possession of dangerous ordnance, a an aggravated felony of the' b'first degree.' b'sec. (a) any person who acquired a military' b'weapon before the effective date of this section shall file a' b'written application for a license to have and carry the military' b'weapon with the sheriff of the county or safety director or' b'police chief of the municipal corporation where the applicant' b'resides or has his principal place of business. the application' b'shall be filed no later than the close of business on the seventh' b'day after the effective date of this section and shall be' b'accompanied by a filing fee of fifty dollars. the person shall' b'file a separate application and pay a separate filing fee for' b'each military weapon that he has or intends to carry. the' b'application shall contain all of the following information:' b'(1) the name, age, address, occupation, and business' b'address of the applicant, if the applicant is a natural person,' b'or the name, address, and principal place of business of the' b'applicant, if the applicant is a corporation;' b'(2) a description of the military weapon for which a' b'license is requested, including the serial number and all' b'identification marks;' b'(3) a statement of the purpose for which the military' b'weapon was acquired and for which it is to be possessed, carried,' b'or used;' b'(4) any other information that the issuing authority may' b'require in giving effect to this section;' b'(5) the oath of the applicant that the information on the' b'application is true.' b'(b)(1) no later than the close of business on the' b'fourteenth day after an application for a license to have and' b'carry a military weapon has been filed under division (a) of this' b'section, the issuing authority shall either approve the' b'application and issue a license to the applicant or deny the' b'application and send a letter of denial by ordinary mail to the' b'applicant. after conducting any necessary investigation, the' b'issuing authority shall issue a license to an applicant whom it' b'determines satisfies the following criteria:' b'(a) the applicant is twenty-one years of age or older, if' b'the applicant is a natural person;' b'(b) it appears that the applicant will possess and carry' b"the military weapon as a collector's item or for a legitimate," b'scientific, educational, industrial, or other proper purpose;' b'(c) it appears that the applicant has sufficient' b'competence to have and carry the military weapon and that proper' b'precautions will be taken to ensure the security of the military' b'weapon and the safety of persons and property;' b'(d) the applicant otherswise is not prohibited by law from' b'having or carrying dangerous ordnance.' b'(2) a license issued pursuant to division (b)(1) of this' b'section shall be valid for one year after the date of its' b'issuance. the license shall be renewed pursuant to division' b'(c) of this section.' b'(c)(1) except as provided in division (c)(3) of this' b'section, any person who is issued a license under division (b)(1)' b'of this section shall renew the license by filing an application' b'for renewal by regular mail with the sheriff of the county or the' b'safety director or police chief of the municipal corporation who' b'was the issuing authority of the license. an application for' b'renewal shall be filed annually no later than one year after the' b'date on which the license was issued or last renewed.' b'(2) each sheriff and each safety director and peace officer' b'of a municipal corporation shall make available applications for' b'the renewal of a license issued under division (b)(1) of this' b'section. in the application the applicant, under oath, shall' b'update the information submitted in the previous application for' b'a license or the renewal of a license.' b'the application for the renewal of a license shall be' b'accompanied by a fee of five dollars. the applicant shall file a' b'seperate application for renewal and pay a seperate renewal fee' b'for each military weapon that he intends to continue to have and' b'carry.' b'(3) a person who has changed his residence or principal' b'place of business to a location outside of the jurisdiction of' b'the issuing authority subsequent to the issuance or renewal of a' b'license under this section shall renew his license by filing an' b'application in the manner prescribed by division (a) of this' b'section with the sheriff of the county or the safety director or' b'police chief of the municipal corporation where he then resides' b'or has his principal place of business. when making an' b'application to renew a license after a change in residence or' b'place of business, the applicant shall give notice of the change' b'of address by regular mail to the original issuing authority for' b'the license and the state fire marshall on notification forms' b'prescribed by the sheriff, safety director, or police chief from' b'whom he seeks renewal.' b'(d) a license to have and carry a military weapon shall' b'identify the person to whom it is issued, identify the military' b'weapon for which it is issued, state the purpose identified in' b'division (b)(1)(b) of this section for which the military weapon' b'will be possessed and carried, state its expiration date, and' b'list all restrictions on the having or carrying of the military' b'weapon as prescribed by the laws of this state and applicable' b'federal law.' b'(e) any person who is issued a license to have and carry a' b'military weapon under this section and who changes his address' b'shall notify the issuing authority of the change of his address' b'no later than ninety days after the change has occurred.' b'(f) the issuing authority shall forward to the state fire' b'marshall a copy of each license issued or renewed under this' b'section. the state fire marshall shall keep a permanent file of' b'all licenses issued or renewed under this section.' b'(g) the issuing authority shall cause each application fee' b'of fifty dollars, filed under division (a) of this section, to be' b'deposited in the general fund of the county or muncipal' b'corporation served by the issuing authority. the issuing' b'authority shall cause two dollars and fifty cents of each renewal' b'fee, filed under division (c) of this section, to be deposited in' b'the general fund of the county or municipal corporation served by' b'the issuing authority and shall send two dollars and fifty cents' b'of each renewal fee to the treasurer of state for deposit in the' b'state treasury to the credit of the general revenue fund.' b'(h) whoever violates division (a) of this section is' b'guilty of failing to apply for the licensure of a military' b'weapon, a felony of the fourth degree. whoever violates division' b'(c) of this section is guilty of failing to apply for renewal of' b'a license for a military weapon, a misdemeanor of the first' b'degree.' b'(i) a military weapon that is not licensed as required by' b'this section is contraband, as defined in section of the' b'revised code and is subject to forfeiture under section b'of the revised code.' b'sec. (a) no person shall do any of the' b'following:' b'(1) import, manufacture, possess for sale, sell, or' b'furnish to any person any military weapon;' b'(2) recklessly sell, lend, give, or furnish any firearm to' b'any person prohibited by section or of the' b'revised code from acquiring or using any firearm, or recklessly' b'sell, lend, give, or furnish any dangerous ordnance to any person' b'prohibited by section or of the revised' b'code from acquiring or using any dangerous ordnance;' b'(3) possess any firearm or dangerous ordnance with' b'purpose to dispose of it in violation of division (a) of this' b'section;' b'(4) manufacture, possess for sale, sell, or furnish to' b'any person other than a law enforcement agency for authorized use' b'in police work, any brass knuckles, cestus, billy, blackjack,' b'sandbag, switchblade knife, springblade knife, gravity knife, or' b'similar weapon;' b'(5) when transferring any dangerous ordnance to' b'another, negligently fail to require the transferes to exhibit' b'any identification, license, or permit showing him to be' b'authorized to acquire dangerous ordnance pursuant to section' b'2923.17 of the revised code, or negligently fail to take a' b'complete record of the transaction and forthwith forward a copy' b'of the record to the sheriff of the county or safety' b'director or police chief of the municipality where the' b'transaction takes place;' b'(6) knowingly fail to report to law enforcement' b'authorities forthwith the loss or theft of any firearm or' b"dangerous ordnance in such person's possession or under his" b'control.' b'(b) whoever violates this section is quilty of unlawful' b'transactions in weapons. violation of division (a)(1) of this' b'section is an aggravated felony of the first degree. violation' b'of division (a)(2) or oof this section is a felony of the' b'third degree. violation of division (a) or of this' b'section is a misdemeanor of the second degree. violation of' b'division of this section is a midemeanor of the fourth' b'degree.' b'section that existing section and' b'2923.20 of the revised code are hereby repealed.' b'section this act is hereby declared to be an emergency' b'measure necessary for the immediate preservation of the public' b'peace, health, and safety. the reason for this necessity is that' b'with immediate action, this act will prohibit the continued' b'purchase, possession, and use of military weapons and as a result' b'will ameliorate a substantial threat of death and injury to the' b'public caused by the misuse of improper use of these weapons.' b'therefore, this act shall go into immediate effect.' b'--' 